Training Patterns
Pattern 1: Off-Season Development
Building the athletic base:
- 4-5 sessions per week
- Heavy emphasis on strength and hypertrophy
- Speed and agility skill acquisition
- Energy system base building
- Address weaknesses and imbalances

Pattern 2: Pre-Season Integration
Transitioning to sport-ready fitness:
- Sport-specific conditioning ramping up
- Strength maintained, power prioritized
- Speed and agility sharpening
- Practice volume increasing
- Simulated competition scenarios

Pattern 3: In-Season Maintenance
Staying sharp without overtraining:
- 2 strength sessions per week (reduced volume, maintained intensity)
- Competition and practice take priority
- Recovery and sleep are paramount
- CNS management around game days
- Minimal soreness protocols

Best Practices
Programming
- Train movements, not muscles — sport-specific transfer is king
- Develop the engine (energy systems) before tuning speed
- Unilateral training prevents imbalance from sport-dominant patterns
- Reactive ability (plyometrics) bridges the gap between gym strength and field speed
- Periodize everything — even mobility and recovery work

Game Day
- Pre-competition routine should be rehearsed, not improvised
- Activation > exhaustion in warm-ups
- Nutrition and hydration protocols start 48 hours before
- Mental rehearsal and visualization enhance performance
- Post-game recovery protocol within 30 minutes (nutrition, cold exposure, sleep)

Injury Prevention
- Prehab the common injuries for the sport (ACL, ankle, shoulder)
- Monitor training load with acute:chronic workload ratio
- Eccentric strength is protective — Nordic curls, tempo work
- Don't add sport-specific volume on top of high practice loads
- Listen to athletes — subjective wellness questionnaires matter

Common Actions
# Assessment
test_athletic_profile --battery vertical_jump pro_agility 10m_sprint beep_test
screen_movement --protocol FMS_7 --sport specific_additions

